            <article data-uuid="7bcb604268ad4bdab5c60877d0e89f3b">
                <h3 class="eq" data-uuid="364e9aef25da414c9ab1260998f0bc1e">Essential Question</h3>
                <h3 class="eqt" data-uuid="8918b9e21e2940d598a633b3224042f4">To what extent did Reconstruction achieve its goals?</h3>
                <p data-uuid="90efdb2328934c36868eb8d2bcebbab8"></p>
                <p data-uuid="995dfd4a6e2042bfa98ad65f9901b571">Following the Civil War, Congress implemented a plan to reconstruct the South. Despite landmark constitutional amendments and the presence of federal troops, gains for southern African Americans were limited. After 12 years, and in response to fierce resistance from many white southerners, the federal government declared Reconstruction over.</p>
                <p data-uuid="575ece449e644c38ac257455fc42d0ca">As you read this module, look for evidence of key events in the Reconstruction period. Note the key people, decisions, circumstances, and turning points that positively or negatively affected the efforts toward unity and equality for all. When you are done, you will write a short essay answering the Essential Question for this module.</p>
            </article>
            <section class="video-container " data-uuid="3b73b2b7db9b439a964051279b010517">
                <article data-uuid="6dfb39b5b7df44568db5c552f3a3e3c3">
                    <h3 class="vid" data-uuid="5c1de189d4e348778dc84e2c3da448a4">Lincoln’s Legacy</h3>
                    <p class="vid" data-uuid="72df2447bb9940a9802c4bdfc1b2993e">In March 1865, Abraham Lincoln delivered his second inaugural address. In his speech, Lincoln outlined a plan to reunite the nation. He had hoped for a spirit of healing and reconciliation. Just a month later, however, an assassin ended Lincoln’s life. Reconstruction would follow a different path than the president intended.</p>
